# Redis ACL — locked-down hot-path metering user.
#
# Rendered at container boot by:
#   sed 's|__PASSWORD__|$REDIS_PASSWORD|' redis-acl.conf.tmpl > /tmp/users.acl
# (handled in the redis service `command:` in deploy/docker-compose.yml).
#
# Security rationale (worthless-c3ox):
#  - `default off` disables unauthenticated access entirely. Without
#    this, an attacker on the backend network can SET/FLUSHALL freely.
#  - `worthless` is the only enabled user. -@all then explicit allow-
#    list bounds the command surface to exactly what SpendCapRule and
#    record_spend need (GET / SET / INCRBY / DEL / PING) plus the
#    redis-py connection-handshake commands (auth / hello / client).
#  - `~worthless:spend:*` scopes keys to our namespace. An attacker
#    with the password can only touch counters they can already read
#    via the proxy — no lateral access to other Redis users' data on
#    a shared instance.
#  - `&*` is the pubsub channel pattern (none used; explicit deny).
#  - `-@dangerous` does NOT include FLUSHALL/FLUSHDB (research
#    footgun #7); that's why we use `-@all` + explicit allow-list.
#
# This file is mounted read-only. ACL SAVE will fail (intentional —
# ACL is immutable in this deploy; rotation requires a re-render).

user default off

user worthless on >__PASSWORD__ ~worthless:spend:* &* -@all +get +set +incrby +del +ping +auth +hello +client|setname
